WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.160 --> 00:00:05.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:23.170 --> 00:00:26.750
&gt;&gt; These extremely rare
but damaged motion pictures

00:00:26.750 --> 00:00:31.090
of Mark Twain were taken at his
home in Connecticut in 1909,

00:00:31.090 --> 00:00:33.150
a year before his death.

00:00:33.150 --> 00:00:36.940
A copy of the film, along with
first editions and thousands

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:40.010
of the celebrated writer's
letters and manuscripts,

00:00:40.010 --> 00:00:42.380
are part of the Mark
Twain Project.

00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:45.870
Its aim is to painstakingly
edit and publish the bulk

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:48.560
of Twain's huge output.

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:51.010
Twain's daughter bequeathed
her father's papers

00:00:51.010 --> 00:00:55.710
to the University of
California at Berkeley in 1962.

00:00:55.710 --> 00:00:59.540
The extensive collection is
hidden away in small offices

00:00:59.540 --> 00:01:02.950
on the top floor of
Bancroft Library.

00:01:02.950 --> 00:01:06.150
For three decades, eight editors
have been pouring over more

00:01:06.150 --> 00:01:09.100
than 10,000 letters,
plus notebooks,

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:12.460
story and book manuscripts
and newspaper clippings,

00:01:12.460 --> 00:01:16.290
seeking to find the real
Mark Twain and to make all

00:01:16.290 --> 00:01:18.490
of his work accurate
and accessible.

00:01:18.490 --> 00:01:22.070
&gt;&gt; This is your literary
heritage here in our files.

00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:25.230
It has to be edited, it has
to be preserved in some form

00:01:25.230 --> 00:01:28.950
that is going to be
transmittable to the future.

00:01:28.950 --> 00:01:30.700
&gt;&gt; Robert Hirst,
the general editor,

00:01:30.700 --> 00:01:34.660
has devoted his entire
professional life since 1967

00:01:34.660 --> 00:01:38.200
to Twain, whom he sees
as a towering talent

00:01:38.200 --> 00:01:39.700
in language and humor.

00:01:39.700 --> 00:01:43.150
&gt;&gt; I still hear my editors
laughing out loud down the hall

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:44.450
because they're reading
something

00:01:44.450 --> 00:01:46.670
which they've probably
read a dozen times before,

00:01:46.670 --> 00:01:49.460
but is still alive
and still funny,

00:01:49.460 --> 00:01:51.780
no matter how many
times you read it.

00:01:51.780 --> 00:01:53.420
&gt;&gt; Many academics would argue

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:56.130
that Twain is still
America's best loved,

00:01:56.130 --> 00:01:58.460
perhaps its best writer.

00:01:58.460 --> 00:02:00.860
Professor Frederick
Crews recently retired

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:02.750
from Berkeley's English
department.

00:02:02.750 --> 00:02:07.510
&gt;&gt; Mark Twain appeals to
academics and non-academics

00:02:07.510 --> 00:02:10.960
to a degree that you can't find
matched in any other writer.

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:12.730
He grew up with the country.

00:02:12.730 --> 00:02:15.900
He represents the
Midwest, the Far West,

00:02:15.900 --> 00:02:18.170
even the New England
establishment.

00:02:18.170 --> 00:02:20.980
He went from being a
rough frontier humorists

00:02:20.980 --> 00:02:25.090
to being the darling
of genteel culture.

00:02:25.090 --> 00:02:27.500
Which of course he made fun of.

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:30.930
&gt;&gt; Robert Pack Browning,
another of the project editors,

00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:33.670
is convinced Twain is
worth special treatment

00:02:33.670 --> 00:02:36.360
as an American writer
and personality.

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:38.990
Using materials from
Berkeley's collection,

00:02:38.990 --> 00:02:43.000
he has put together an exciting
display of Twain's life and work

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.580
at the University's
Blackhawk Museum.

00:02:45.580 --> 00:02:48.360
&gt;&gt; The language that
you and I speak

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:53.490
with its peculiar
American qualities,

00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:56.020
was put down on paper
by this man.

00:02:56.020 --> 00:02:58.130
&gt;&gt; Notice his handwriting.

00:02:58.130 --> 00:03:00.590
&gt;&gt; At the museum,
visitors immerse themselves

00:03:00.590 --> 00:03:05.130
in the issues Twain wrote about,
from racial equality to love.

00:03:05.130 --> 00:03:08.450
A passionate love letter
to his future wife is here

00:03:08.450 --> 00:03:10.890
for everybody to read.

00:03:10.890 --> 00:03:16.410
&gt;&gt; I love love love love love
you, and multiplied by 150.

00:03:16.410 --> 00:03:18.810
And so loving you,
I note your faults,

00:03:18.810 --> 00:03:20.230
ignite them with my love.

00:03:20.230 --> 00:03:23.010
&gt;&gt; What do you think
that Mark Twain feels

00:03:23.010 --> 00:03:24.920
about this wonderful woman?

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:26.310
&gt;&gt; He was really
in love with her.

00:03:26.310 --> 00:03:27.900
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:03:27.900 --> 00:03:30.450
&gt;&gt; Twain spent a lot of
time on the lecture circuit

00:03:30.450 --> 00:03:32.530
to gain fame and money.

00:03:32.530 --> 00:03:36.920
His lecture notes from 1896
help explain the crucial passage

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:39.890
in Huck Finn published
12 years earlier,

00:03:39.890 --> 00:03:41.710
where Huck is debating
whether to turn

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:44.380
in Jim as a runaway slave.

00:03:44.380 --> 00:03:48.830
&gt;&gt; Huck is prepared to turn Jim
in, yet he finally concludes

00:03:48.830 --> 00:03:50.410
that he cannot do that.

00:03:50.410 --> 00:03:55.050
His heart wins out and his
conscience suffers a defeat.

00:03:55.050 --> 00:04:00.630
This was the most popular
component of his lecture

00:04:00.630 --> 00:04:05.000
on this grand tour of the world.

