00:09:24.310 --> 00:09:26.800
but there are some terrific
Mark Twain materials here

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:28.270
in the Library of Congress.

00:09:28.270 --> 00:09:29.860
One of them is up on the screen.

00:09:29.860 --> 00:09:32.380
In 1874, Mark Twain --

00:09:32.380 --> 00:09:35.820
who of course his real
name was Samuel Clemens --

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:38.530
he wrote a letter to the
Librarian of Congress.

00:09:38.530 --> 00:09:42.730
And he did so because he had
written a series of sketches

00:09:42.730 --> 00:09:46.470
and he wanted to ensure that
his work was being copyrighted.

00:09:46.470 --> 00:09:49.920
You can go ahead and
hit that next slide.

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:55.860
So he's writing to -- this is
in May of 1874, and he's writing

00:09:55.860 --> 00:09:59.590
to the then Librarian of
Congress, Ainsworth Spofford.

00:09:59.590 --> 00:10:03.830
He says, "Dear sir, I enclose a
design of a pamphlet cover upon

00:10:03.830 --> 00:10:05.550
which I desire copyright.

00:10:05.550 --> 00:10:09.030
Also, the title page of the
pamphlet, upon the contents

00:10:09.030 --> 00:10:11.900
of which I likewise
desire copyright.

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:15.420
Fees, $1, enclosed.

00:10:15.420 --> 00:10:18.500
Very truly yours,
Samuel Clemens."

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:21.380
So we have to say, we love
it when we come across things

00:10:21.380 --> 00:10:23.020
like this in the
Library's collection.

00:10:23.020 --> 00:10:25.630
So a handwritten letter
from Mark Twain related

00:10:25.630 --> 00:10:28.100
to copywriting some of his work.

00:10:28.100 --> 00:10:31.420
But not only does the Library of
Congress hold original letters,

00:10:31.420 --> 00:10:34.780
but the Library also has
an enormous collection

00:10:34.780 --> 00:10:38.760
of newspapers and magazines
and many, many, many --

00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:40.060
literally millions of them --

00:10:40.060 --> 00:10:43.860
are available through
the Library's Chronicling

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:45.220
America website.

00:10:45.220 --> 00:10:47.690
And the next slide,
which shows you one

00:10:47.690 --> 00:10:51.600
of those political cartoons
in one of those magazines,

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:55.660
Harper's Weekly, that
shows Mark Twain as well.

00:10:55.660 --> 00:10:57.690
And I know that in your
textbooks and other materials,

00:10:57.690 --> 00:10:59.320
sometimes -- go ahead
and click it again --

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:03.540
you often see things like
the political cartoon,

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:05.240
but you miss the context.

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:07.200
You sort of miss that
it originally appeared

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:09.730
in the newspaper, and that's
the fun part about looking

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:12.960
at original sources, is you see
where they originally came from.

